 Yes, you can create a flush-left array in LaTeX by using the `\begin{array}{l}` environment. The `l` parameter specifies left alignment for the column.

Here's how to use it:

```latex
\begin{array}{l}
\text{First line of the array} \\
\text{Second line of the array} \\
\text{Third line of the array}
\end{array}
```

If you need multiple columns that are all left-aligned, you can use:

```latex
\begin{array}{lll}
\text{Row 1, Col 1} & \text{Row 1, Col 2} & \text{Row 1, Col 3} \\
\text{Row 2, Col 1} & \text{Row 2, Col 2} & \text{Row 2, Col 3}
\end{array}
```

You can also use the `flalign` or `flalign*` environment from the `amsmath` package for equations that are flush with the left margin:

```latex
\begin{flalign*}
&\text{This equation will be flush left:} &\\
&E = mc^2 &
\end{flalign*}
```

The `flalign` environment is specifically designed for left-aligned equations.

